# Joins — types & the duplicate-column trap

## `df1.join(df2, on, how)` — six kinds

- **`inner`** (default) · **`left`** / **`right`** / **`full`** (outer, null-fill)
- **`left_semi`** — rows of `df1` *with* a match (no `df2` cols)
- **`left_anti`** — rows of `df1` *without* a match · **`cross`** — Cartesian

## Two ways to name the key

- **String** `join(df2, "k")` — same name → Spark **de-duplicates** the key
- **Expression** `df1.x == df2.y` — different names → both columns survive

## The trap

- Expression form on same-named cols → **two** `k` columns → `select("k")` is **ambiguous**
- Null keys never match (null-unsafe `=`) → use **`eqNullSafe`** if needed
